Two purrr patterns worth memorizing
The “model per group” pipeline. Probably the highest-leverage pattern in the entire tutorial:
gapminder |&gt;
  group_by(continent) |&gt;
  nest() |&gt;
  mutate(
    model    = map(data, \(d) lm(lifeExp ~ pop + gdpPercap + year, data = d)),
    tidy_out = map(model, broom::tidy)
  ) |&gt;
  ungroup() |&gt;
  transmute(continent, tidy_out) |&gt;
  unnest(tidy_out)
This produces one tidy tibble with one row per continent × term, with estimates, standard errors, p-values — ready for ggplot or gt. The shape generalizes: anywhere you’d otherwise loop over groups, fit something, extract something, and bind back, the nest → mutate(map) → unnest pipeline does it in one breath.
reduce() for repeated binary operations. When you need to apply the same binary operation across a list — joining many tables on a common key, row-binding many tibbles, intersecting many sets — reduce() is the right tool:
list_of_tables |&gt; reduce(left_join, by = "id")     # join all on "id"
list_of_tibbles |&gt; reduce(bind_rows)               # row-bind all
list_of_logical_vectors |&gt; reduce(`&`)             # element-wise AND
The pattern is “fold the list into a single result by repeatedly applying a binary operation.” accumulate() is the same thing but keeps the intermediate results, useful for cumulative diagnostics.

Two patterns that compose JSON + URL + urltools
Building a parameterized URL programmatically. Rather than concatenating strings:
base &lt;- "https://api.census.gov/data/2020/acs/acs1"
url &lt;- base |&gt;
  urltools::param_set("get", "NAME,B01001_001E") |&gt;
  urltools::param_set("for", "state:*") |&gt;
  urltools::param_set("key", api_key)
Each param_set() call is independent and order-insensitive. Compared to paste0(base, "?get=NAME&for=state:*&key=", api_key), this is robust against missing values, accidental double &, and special characters that need encoding.
Parsing a JSON response into a tidy tibble. A typical response shape — array of objects with some nested fields:
resp &lt;- httr2::request(url) |&gt; httr2::req_perform()
data &lt;- httr2::resp_body_json(resp)

# data is a list of lists. Convert to tibble:
tibble(record = data) |&gt;
  unnest_wider(record) |&gt;
  unnest_longer(authors)   # if 'authors' is an array
unnest_wider flattens a column of lists-of-named-things into multiple columns (one per name). unnest_longer expands an array column into multiple rows. Together they tame almost any JSON shape into a tabular one.

Two patterns worth memorizing
The dbplyr workflow shape. This is the canonical pipeline for using a database from R:
con &lt;- DBI::dbConnect(duckdb::duckdb(), dbdir = "data/my.duckdb")

# Reference, doesn't load anything
flights_db &lt;- tbl(con, "flights")

# Compose a query lazily
delayed_flights &lt;- flights_db |&gt;
  filter(arr_delay &gt; 60) |&gt;
  group_by(dest) |&gt;
  summarize(n = n(), avg_delay = mean(arr_delay, na.rm = TRUE)) |&gt;
  arrange(desc(n))

# Inspect what would run
delayed_flights |&gt; show_query()

# Pull results into R when ready
result &lt;- delayed_flights |&gt; collect()

DBI::dbDisconnect(con)
Connect → reference → compose → inspect → collect. Doing it in this order means you only pull computed results, never the underlying table.
The “see what SQL it generates” trick for learning. The fastest way to learn SQL given dplyr fluency:
flights_db |&gt;
  filter(dest == "IAH") |&gt;
  group_by(carrier) |&gt;
  summarize(avg_delay = mean(arr_delay, na.rm = TRUE)) |&gt;
  arrange(desc(avg_delay)) |&gt;
  show_query()
Read the output. Match each line to a dplyr verb. After 10 such pipelines, the SQL clause vocabulary becomes familiar. This is how the chapter teaches; it’s also how to keep learning whenever you hit a new pattern.

